SIMPLE: convulse
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Convulse
<hw>Con*vulse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Convulsed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Convulsing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>convulsus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>convellere</ets> to tear up, to
shake; <ets>con-</ets> + <ets>vellere</ets> to pluck, pull.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To contract violently and irregularly, as the muscular
parts of an animal body; to shake with irregular spasms, as in excessive
laughter, or in agony from grief or pain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With emotions which checked his voice and <qex>convulsed</qex> his
powerful frame.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To agitate greatly; to shake violently.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The world is <qex>convulsed by the agonies of great
nations</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To agitate; disturb; shake; tear; rend.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Convulsion</ent>⟦br⟧
